Spring Boot 4.1.0 app will stop responding after 60+ secs of inactivity when the following setup is used:

 * Jetty is set as an embedded web server
 * Virtual Thread support is enabled in Spring Boot.
 * App runs on JVM 21+
 * Important: Spring Actuator is **enabled** and it is configured to use a **different port**. In this project it uses port 9090 while main server uses port 8080.

Note:
The same issue can be reproduced in 3.5.x branch with Spring Boot 3.5.7+.
Apparently this change made to the JettyVirtualThreadsWebServerFactoryCustomizer class introduced the problem:
https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/commit/128975945b724a02793d51c06da075d68768c4fa

If you run the app  with Spring Boot 3.5.6 the problem will not appear.

Also, the problem will NOT appear in any Spring Boot version if Spring Actuator is not enabled or it shares the same port with the main server.

Test project to reproduce the problem:
https://github.com/alex-best-pf/spring-boot-jetty 

According to the Jetty doc https://jetty.org/docs/jetty/12.1/programming-guide/arch/threads.html#thread-pool-virtual-threads-queued we should set a VirtualThreadPool as a an Executor in QueuedThreadPool  instance and pass the QueuedThreadPool to the server.

```java
  QueuedThreadPool threadPool = new QueuedThreadPool();

// Simple, unlimited, virtual thread Executor.
threadPool.setVirtualThreadsExecutor(Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor());

// Configurable, bounded, virtual thread executor (preferred).
VirtualThreadPool virtualExecutor = new VirtualThreadPool();
virtualExecutor.setMaxConcurrentTasks(128);
threadPool.setVirtualThreadsExecutor(virtualExecutor);

// For server-side usage.
Server server = new Server(threadPool);

// Simple client-side usage.
HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
client.setExecutor(threadPool);
````

Proposed fix:
in this file https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/v4.1.0/module/spring-boot-jetty/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/jetty/autoconfigure/JettyVirtualThreadsWebServerFactoryCustomizer.java

in a "customize" method

Create QueuedThreadPool instance, set the VirtualThreadsExecutor to the VirtualThreadPool  and then set the ThreadPool of the factory to the QueuedThreadPool  instead of VirtualThreadPool  

```java
	@Override
	public void customize(ConfigurableJettyWebServerFactory factory) {
		Assert.state(VirtualThreads.areSupported(), "Virtual threads are not supported");
		Integer maxTasks = getMaxTasks();
		VirtualThreadPool virtualThreadPool = (maxTasks != null) ? new VirtualThreadPool(maxTasks)
				: new VirtualThreadPool();
		virtualThreadPool.setName("jetty-");
                QueuedThreadPool threadPool = new QueuedThreadPool();
                threadPool.setVirtualThreadsExecutor(virtualThreadPool );
		factory.setThreadPool(threadPool);
	}
```

